Background

This report provides a brief summary of the weekly ensemble forecast from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub based on forecasts submitted on September 19, 2022. In collaboration with the US CDC, our team aggregates COVID-19 forecasts from dozens of teams around the globe. Typically on Wednesday of each week, a summary of the week's forecasts from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub appear on the official CDC COVID-19 forecasting page.

Every week, teams submit their forecasts to the COVID-19 Forecast Hub. This past week, 36 models were submitted.

Each Monday evening or Tuesday morning, we combine the most recent forecasts from each team into a single "ensemble" forecast of reported COVID-19 cases at the county, state, and national level and deaths at the state and national level. At the moment, we only generate ensemble forecasts for up to four weeks into the future, as the available evidence suggests that models are less accurate at longer forecast horizons.

An archive of weekly reports from the COVID-19 Forecast Hub can be found at this page.

COVID-19 Forecasts

National level

This week, our ensemble combined forecasts from 29 different models.

At the national level, the ensemble model predicts that weekly totals of observed deaths in each of the next four weeks will be between 2,300 and 2,700 deaths with around 1,063,600 deaths by October 15, 2022 (95% prediction interval: 1,061,293 - 1,067,537).

For the week ending October 15, 2022, the ensemble forecasts that reported COVID-19 deaths in the US will be between 1,600 and 3,900 (95% prediction interval: 1,601 - 3,938).

As of September 28, 2021 the ensemble forecast only reports one-week ahead forecasts for cases and 14 day ahead forecasts for hospitalizations, due to persistent large inaccuracies observed when forecasting beyond that.

For October 03, 2022 COVID-19 daily hospitalizations in the US will be between 1,700 and 6,300 (95% prediction interval: 1,735 - 6,305).

For the week ending September 24, 2022, the ensemble forecasts that reported COVID-19 cases in the US will be between 263,700 and 578,600 (95% prediction interval: 263,652 - 578,581).

You can explore the full set of models, including their forecasts for past weeks online at the Forecast Hub interactive visualization.

State level

The ensemble model estimates that 13 out of 50 states and 3 out of 7 territories of the US have a greater than 50% chance of having more deaths in the next two weeks compared to the past two weeks.The model forecasts that 4 states and territories have a greater than 75% chance of an increase over the next two weeks (District of Columbia, North Carolina, American Samoa, Northern Mariana Islands).

Looking at the rates allows for easier comparison across states, where you can see which states have had or are predicted to have proportionally higher rates in comparison to other states.

When interpreting probability of an increase, it's important to note that the increase or decrease is relative to the location-specific recent observed incidence, which varies across locations.
